newsitem.title: INDONESIA: Jakarta call money traded at 14.5/15.0 percent.
newsitem.headline: Jakarta call money traded at 14.5/15.0 percent.

text.p: Jakarta call money was traded at 14.5/15.0 percent on Wednesday morning, dealers said.
One local bank dealer said liquidity supply seemed to be sufficient despite a neutral central bank money policy.
He said interbank rates were driven up by expensive short-dated swap rates following liquidity concerns.
But dealers said longer-term money remained stable, with one-month money quoted at around 14.50/14.75 percent.
One foreign bank dealer said operators appeared to be preparing for Friday and next Tuesday, when tax payments are due. He said payments are likely to be relatively high.
The average overnight initerbank rate on Tuesday was 14.26 percent, compared with 14.11 percent on Monday.
